24
00:02:29,309 --> 00:02:33,872
So tonight presenting specific targeted proposed city charter amendments.

25
00:02:34,252 --> 00:02:40,096
There are three common sense measures to increase transparency, accountability, and democratic oversight in Medford city government.

26
00:02:42,057 --> 00:02:43,338
First, I'm going to start with a why.

27
00:02:43,918 --> 00:02:50,582
The reason that I'm proposing this is as I just outlined that Medford needs a more open budget process and a city council with real oversight authority.

28
00:02:51,523 --> 00:02:56,526
The Medford city charter, as I mentioned, is one of the most unbalanced strong mayor city charters in Massachusetts.

29
00:02:57,378 --> 00:03:10,651
Pretty much every elected official in the city agrees that the office of the mayor of Medford is one of the strongest mayors in the entire state of Massachusetts, and that, as such, the weak city council under that system holds very limited authority for oversight and accountability.

30
00:03:11,552 --> 00:03:21,342
These targeted charter amendments that I will go into in a minute can significantly improve the transparency of city government by providing the city council with powers that many other city councils in Massachusetts have.

31
00:03:22,542 --> 00:03:26,846
Another reason why is that residents deserve a voice in the city budget process through the city council.

32
00:03:27,707 --> 00:03:31,351
Right now the city council has almost no authority over the city budget process.

33
00:03:31,391 --> 00:03:44,743
I think we've all experienced the confusion that gets created when the city council can only approve, reject or cut from the mayor's budget proposals and the inability of counselors to really address the concerns of residents.

34
00:03:45,584 --> 00:03:50,728
And then finally, the city council needs true independence as a separate branch of city government.

35
00:03:50,748 --> 00:04:04,018
I think we've all seen that while we work often closely with city staff hired by the mayor's city administration, there's situations that come up where the city council requires independent staff advice or legal representation.

36
00:04:04,579 --> 00:04:08,902
Under the current charter, the council can only receive that independent support with the approval of the mayor.

37
00:04:09,848 --> 00:04:19,812
And also the city council does not prove the mayor's appointments to boards and commissions, which means that we don't really have equal status as a separate branch of city government.

38
00:04:24,474 --> 00:04:37,059
These three amendments, which I'll go into more detail later, to fix that would one, give the city council a voice in the budget process by allowing the city council to amend the mayor's budget proposal, which of course the mayor could then veto.

39
00:04:38,430 --> 00:04:45,492
Secondly, it would put into the city charter that the city council is allowed to hire staff members and independent legal advice and support.

40
00:04:46,172 --> 00:04:52,414
And finally, it would require that the city council confirms the appointees of the mayor to city boards and commissions.

41
00:04:55,275 --> 00:04:59,657
So under Massachusetts general law, there are several ways to amend the city charter.

42
00:05:01,478 --> 00:05:07,442
What we've heard over many years and what we currently have a charter study committee looking at is something called charter review.

43
00:05:07,922 --> 00:05:18,610
And this is the process of creating an entirely new city charter, or going through the existing city charter and making extensive revisions under that process you can alter any provision of the city charter.

44
00:05:19,190 --> 00:05:23,195
There's a few different ways to go about that, but to go into the two main ones.

45
00:05:23,836 --> 00:05:38,032
One is that voters could sign an initiative petition to create a charter commission, which then voters would elect commission members, the commission would hold hearings, make a recommendation, and then voters would approve or reject that recommendation.

46
00:05:39,262 --> 00:05:55,992
The other way is the special act charter, where the city council could form a review committee, the charter study committee, like we have now, or could petition the state legislature through a home rule petition to create an elected charter commission, which is something that's come before this body several times in the past few years.

47
00:05:56,392 --> 00:06:02,476
And then again, that committee or elected commission would make a recommendation, voters would approve or reject it.

48
00:06:02,696 --> 00:06:08,019
The city council could then vote with the mayor's approval to send a special act charter proposal to the state legislature.

49
00:06:08,607 --> 00:06:12,429
And if the legislature approved, that new charter would then go into effect.

50
00:06:13,129 --> 00:06:16,791
What we're talking about today is something completely different from charter review.

51
00:06:17,371 --> 00:06:20,072
It is amending specific charter provisions.

52
00:06:20,513 --> 00:06:25,735
And this is done under Massachusetts general law chapter 43 section, 43B section 10.

53
00:06:26,295 --> 00:06:32,598
There's specific restrictions on what changes the council can propose or the council or community can propose under this provision.

54
00:06:33,059 --> 00:06:35,580
You cannot change the composition of elected bodies

55
00:06:36,020 --> 00:06:38,221
the mode of election or the terms of office.

56
00:06:38,241 --> 00:06:48,505
So things like ward representation or changing who's on the school committee or changing term limits, for example, or extending the mayor term are not allowed under this process.

57
00:06:48,945 --> 00:06:54,607
However, the three amendments that I am proposing tonight would be completely allowed under this process.

58
00:06:54,887 --> 00:07:02,330
And how that would go is we would have to have a two thirds vote of the city council followed by at least one public hearing within three months.

59
00:07:03,030 --> 00:07:04,211
The approval of the mayor

60
00:07:04,980 --> 00:07:13,046
which, and then the amendments will be reviewed by the attorney general before going on the ballot for the voters of the city of Medford to approve or reject those amendments.

61
00:07:14,527 --> 00:07:18,449
As you can see here, well, that's not the right screen, is it?

62
00:07:18,589 --> 00:07:19,470
But we'll go here.

63
00:07:20,130 --> 00:07:29,317
This is what, this black box, that's the process we're looking at here under Massachusetts General Law, Chapter 43B, Section 10, and a little bit of Section 11.

64
00:07:31,683 --> 00:07:40,867
One of the key differences here is that the amending of specific charter provision can happen much, much faster than a charter review can happen.

65
00:07:41,107 --> 00:07:58,375
So if we were to move forward with this tonight, we could hold a council vote to start the process and hold public hearings over the next several weeks before coming up with a final proposal, which would then go to the mayor for approval and then go through attorney general review.

66
00:07:59,003 --> 00:08:03,866
And that would happen by about July 2023 after the full process would go into effect.

67
00:08:04,427 --> 00:08:12,052
That would allow these specific amendments to go on the ballot this November for this municipal election and to go into effect next January.

68
00:08:13,080 --> 00:08:22,326
Now, a charter commission, which we currently don't have an elected one, if voters were to gather enough signatures, the earliest that that commission could be elected would be November 2023.

69
00:08:22,906 --> 00:08:26,208
They would then have 18 months to propose something.

70
00:08:26,648 --> 00:08:29,970
Voters would then have to approve their recommendation, which would likely happen in November 2025.

71
00:08:31,311 --> 00:08:33,952
And the new charter wouldn't go in effect until January 2028.

72
00:08:36,408 --> 00:08:54,378
Under the special act process, the review committee can set its own timeline, but still very likely, I don't believe at least currently that a charter would be on the ballot, a charter would be on the ballot for this election, certainly in November, 2023, it would likely be on the ballot in November, 2024 or November, 2025.

73
00:08:54,959 --> 00:08:58,781
And then again, the charter would not go into effect until January, 2026 or January, 2028.

74
00:09:04,215 --> 00:09:11,657
So a couple of additional key facts here, as I was saying, you know, the city council would hold public hearings.

75
00:09:11,717 --> 00:09:18,439
If we were to move forward, I would propose that we hold two public hearings, one in the subcommittee on ordinances and rules to invite feedback.

76
00:09:18,900 --> 00:09:24,021
And then another committee of the whole public hearing to incorporate additional public feedback into any final proposal.

77
00:09:25,502 --> 00:09:30,063
Secondly, the city council could place these amendment language on the ballot without mayoral approval.

78
00:09:30,732 --> 00:09:40,950
The only difference between that would be that they are non-binding in that case, so it would not be a binding procedure under Chapter 43B, Section 10.

79
00:09:43,274 --> 00:09:53,037
And finally, something that's again, really important to remember, this is a completely separate from the charter review and the existing charter study committee that exists.

80
00:09:53,778 --> 00:10:09,983
And that the existing charter study committee or a future elected charter commission could change these amendments, remove them, amend them, add them, adjust them when they review the charter and propose a full comprehensive charter review.

81
00:10:10,598 --> 00:10:12,719
a new charter at whichever point that happens.

82
00:10:13,740 --> 00:10:17,081
So again, I wanted to keep that relatively short and sweet.

83
00:10:17,622 --> 00:10:32,850
Here's some of the sources that I used for this presentation, and I'm happy to entertain further discussion with my council colleagues to go through the specific language of the proposals or really anywhere else anyone wants to take this.

84
00:10:33,090 --> 00:10:33,430
Thank you.

85
